{"key":"post-17397944","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>17397944</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; A fully colonized cake does not show even the slightest mark or indentation.&amp;nbsp; It's really as if the shroom was never there. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This is entirely strain dependent.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Some strains are firmly attached to the substrate and others only have a tiny attachment point and the mushrooms twist off easily.&amp;nbsp; Strains in which the fruits are firmly attached to the substrate will suffer considerable damage to the cake or casing layer if they're ripped out.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Obviously one needs to evaluate conditions to determine which way will cause the least damage.&amp;nbsp; The stumps left over from picking firmly attached fruits do not rot.&amp;nbsp; However, a divot in the substrate from ripping out a large chunk is almost guaranteed to have green mold before the next flush finishes.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>17399227</next>\n<prev>17397917</prev>\n<first>17394026</first>\n<last>17400912</last>\n<when>1355618636</when>\n<utime>12/16/12 02:43 AM</utime>\n</post>"}